i was thinking about how you said if i told you that i saw a squirrel grab a nut then you would believe me without much convincing.  this is only because you know that squirrels exist based on personal experience.  objective reality says that squirrels exist so it doesn't matter if I was born and raised in antarctica without any access to squirrels, they still exist but they do not exist for me, unless of course I choose to exercise faith.  the fact remains that the universe is huge and we live in a much smaller place than antarctica comparatively.<br>
<br>
squirrels exist in objective reality and, as the one separated from the rest of the universe, the only choices i can see is to exercise faith or live without the knowledge of squirrels.  same goes for god and the &quot;super force&quot; described in the big bang theory.<br>
<br>
the choice each individual makes will no doubt vary, from person to person and from situation to situation.  the fact that billions choose to exercise faith doesn't make them arrogant.  there's a much stronger case for arrogance in thinking that as a speck in the universe, all there is to know can be objectively explained right now in our current circumstances.  ( that's one smart speck <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    )<br>
